  "reasoning": "1) The spinner is a full circle, so total central angles sum to 360°. There are six regions: four of size x°, one of 20°, and one of 140°. Thus: 4x + 20 + 140 = 360 ⇒ 4x + 160 = 360 ⇒ 4x = 200 ⇒ x = 50°. 2) The shaded regions are the 140° region plus two of the x° regions. Total shaded angle: θ = 140 + 2·50 = 140 + 100 = 240°. 3) N is defined as N = θ + 2700 = 240 + 2700 = 2940. 4) We are told (205800, 35k) is a happy pair if gcd(205800, 35k) is a perfect square. Let g = gcd(205800, 35k). First factor: 205800. Prime factorization: 205800 = 2058 · 100 = (2 · 3 · 7 · 7 · 7) · (2² · 5²) = 2³ · 3¹ · 5² · 7³. 5) Factor 35k: 35k = 5 · 7 · k. Then g = gcd(205800, 35k) = gcd(2³ · 3¹ · 5² · 7³, 5¹ · 7¹ · k). We can write g = 5^a · 7^b · d, where d divides k and is composed only of primes 2 and 3, but 35k only includes 2 and 3 insofar as they appear in k. More concretely, let k = 2^α · 3^β · 5^γ · 7^δ · r, where r is coprime to 2,3,5,7. Then: - gcd factor for 2: min(3, α) - gcd factor for 3: min(1, β) - gcd factor for 5: min(2, γ+1), since 35k has 5^(γ+1) - gcd factor for 7: min(3, δ+1), since 35k has 7^(δ+1). All exponents in g must be even for g to be a perfect square. So we get four parity conditions: (i) min(3, α) even, (ii) min(1, β) even, (iii) min(2, γ+1) even, (iv) min(3, δ+1) even. Also, note that primes in r do not appear in 205800 or 35 except possibly through k, but since gcd requires presence in both numbers, any prime in r (coprime to 2,3,5,7) appears only in k and not in 205800 or 35; hence those primes do not appear in gcd at all. So only primes 2,3,5,7 matter, and the conditions only involve α,β,γ,δ. 6) Condition on β: min(1, β) is 0 if β=0, and 1 if β≥1. For it to be even, we must have min(1, β) = 0 ⇒ β = 0. So k must not be divisible by 3. 7) Condition on α: min(3, α). Values: - α=0 ⇒ min(3,0)=0 (even) - α=1 ⇒ 1 (odd) - α=2 ⇒ 2 (even) - α≥3 ⇒ 3 (odd). So allowed α are 0 or 2. Thus, k is either not divisible by 2, or divisible by 4 but not by 8. 8) Condition on γ: min(2, γ+1). Values depending on γ: - γ=0 ⇒ γ+1=1 ⇒ min(2,1)=1 (odd) - γ=1 ⇒ γ+1=2 ⇒ min(2,2)=2 (even) - γ≥2 ⇒ γ+1 ≥3 ⇒ min(2,γ+1)=2 (even). So γ ≠ 0. That is, k must be divisible by 5 (at least 5¹). 9) Condition on δ: min(3, δ+1). Values: - δ=0 ⇒ δ+1=1 ⇒ 1 (odd) - δ=1 ⇒ 2 (even) - δ=2 ⇒ 3 (odd) - δ≥3 ⇒ δ+1 ≥4 ⇒ min(3,δ+1)=3 (odd). So only δ=1 works. That is, k must be divisible by 7¹ but not by 7². 10) Summarize necessary and sufficient conditions for k: - β=0: k not divisible by 3. - γ≥1: k divisible by 5. - δ=1: k divisible by 7, but not by 49. - α ∈ {0,2}: either no factor 2, or exactly 2² but not higher. There is no restriction on other primes ≠2,3,5,7: they can appear in any exponent. 11) Next, impose k ≤ N = 2940. We count positive integers k ≤ 2940 satisfying those conditions. It is helpful to write k in the form k = 2^α · 5^γ · 7^δ · u, where α ∈ {0,2}, γ≥1, δ=1, and u is an integer coprime to 2,3,5,7. Moreover, 3 ∤ k is automatically encoded by u coprime to 3 and α,γ,δ not introducing 3. We also require 49 ∤ k; since δ=1, this is satisfied automatically. So k = 2^α · 5^γ · 7 · u with α ∈ {0,2}, γ≥1, and u coprime to 2,3,5,7. 12) Let t = 2^α · 5^γ · 7. Then k = t · u, and the bound is t · u ≤ 2940, with gcd(u, 2·3·5·7)=1. We will enumerate possible (α, γ) and the resulting t values, then for each t count allowed u up to floor(2940/t) that are coprime to 210. 13) Compute possible t values. Note α ∈ {0,2}. For each α, γ≥1 but constrained by t ≤ 2940 because u≥1. Case A: α=0 ⇒ 2^α =1. Then t = 5^γ · 7. We need 5^γ · 7 ≤ 2940 ⇒ 5^γ ≤ 2940/7 = 420. So 5^γ ≤ 420. Check powers: 5¹=5, 5²=25, 5³=125, 5⁴=625>420. So γ ∈ {1,2,3}. Thus t values: - γ=1: t = 5·7 =35 - γ=2: t = 25·7=175 - γ=3: t = 125·7=875 Case B: α=2 ⇒ 2²=4. Then t = 4 · 5^γ · 7 = 28 · 5^γ. Need 28·5^γ ≤ 2940 ⇒ 5^γ ≤ 2940/28 = 105. So 5^γ ≤105 ⇒ γ∈{1,2}. (5³=125 >105). So t values: - γ=1: t = 28·5 =140 - γ=2: t = 28·25=700 So the five t values are {35, 175, 875, 140, 700}. 14) For each t, define M = floor(2940/t). We must count u from 1 to M such that gcd(u,210)=1. The count is φ(210) scaled by the proportion of numbers up to M that are coprime to 210, but more directly we count with inclusion-exclusion using primes 2,3,5,7. However, note: by construction, u is any integer coprime to 2,3,5,7, but t already includes some of these primes; still, gcd(u,210)=1 is the only condition. So for each t, the number of valid u is: count_u(M) = #{1 ≤ u ≤ M : gcd(u,210)=1}. Since 210=2·3·5·7, we can use: count_u(M) = M · φ(210)/210 ± correction for remainder, but simpler and exact: count_u(M) = M - ⌊M/2⌋ - ⌊M/3⌋ - ⌊M/5⌋ - ⌊M/7⌋ + ⌊M/6⌋ + ⌊M/10⌋ + ⌊M/14⌋ + ⌊M/15⌋ + ⌊M/21⌋ + ⌊M/35⌋ - ⌊M/30⌋ - ⌊M/42⌋ - ⌊M/70⌋ - ⌊M/105⌋ + ⌊M/210⌋. This is inclusion-exclusion for the set of primes {2,3,5,7}. 15) We will do this computation for each M corresponding to t. First, compute φ(210) for a check: φ(210)=210(1-1/2)(1-1/3)(1-1/5)(1-1/7)=210·(1/2)·(2/3)·(4/5)·(6/7) = 210·(1/2·2/3=1/3 → 210/3=70; 70·4/5=56; 56·6/7=48). So φ(210)=48. The density of numbers coprime to 210 is 48/210=8/35≈0.228571. We'll use inclusion-exclusion with floor values for exact counts. 16) Compute each M: - For t=35: M1 = ⌊2940/35⌋. 35·80=2800, 35·84=2940. So M1=84. - For t=175: M2 = ⌊2940/175⌋. 175·10=1750, 175·16=2800, 175·17=2975>2940. So M2=16. - For t=875: M3 = ⌊2940/875⌋. 875·3=2625, 875·4=3500>2940. So M3=3. - For t=140: M4 = ⌊2940/140⌋. 140·20=2800, 140·21=2940. So M4=21. - For t=700: M5 = ⌊2940/700⌋. 700·4=2800, 700·5=3500>2940. So M5=4. 17) Now count_u(M) for each M using inclusion-exclusion. Define f(M) = # {1 ≤ u ≤ M : gcd(u,210)=1}. Use formula: f(M) = M - (⌊M/2⌋+⌊M/3⌋+⌊M/5⌋+⌊M/7⌋) + (⌊M/6⌋+⌊M/10⌋+⌊M/14⌋+⌊M/15⌋+⌊M/21⌋+⌊M/35⌋) - (⌊M/30⌋+⌊M/42⌋+⌊M/70⌋+⌊M/105⌋) + ⌊M/210⌋. (All lcms up to product of three primes; the product of all four is 210.) 18) Compute f(84): - Floors: ⌊84/2⌋=42, ⌊84/3⌋=28, ⌊84/5⌋=16, ⌊84/7⌋=12; sum1=42+28+16+12=98. - Pairwise lcms: 6,10,14,15,21,35. Floors: ⌊84/6⌋=14, ⌊84/10⌋=8, ⌊84/14⌋=6, ⌊84/15⌋=5, ⌊84/21⌋=4, ⌊84/35⌋=2; sum2=14+8+6+5+4+2=39. - Triple lcms: 30,42,70,105. Floors: ⌊84/30⌋=2, ⌊84/42⌋=2, ⌊84/70⌋=1, ⌊84/105⌋=0; sum3=2+2+1+0=5. - Quadruple lcm 210: ⌊84/210⌋=0. So f(84) = 84 - 98 + 39 - 5 + 0 = 84 - 98 = -14; -14 +39=25; 25-5=20. So there are 20 valid u for M=84. 19) Compute f(16): - ⌊16/2⌋=8, ⌊16/3⌋=5, ⌊16/5⌋=3, ⌊16/7⌋=2; sum1=8+5+3+2=18. - Pairs: 6,10,14,15,21,35. Floors: ⌊16/6⌋=2, ⌊16/10⌋=1, ⌊16/14⌋=1, ⌊16/15⌋=1, ⌊16/21⌋=0, ⌊16/35⌋=0; sum2=2+1+1+1+0+0=5. - Triples: 30,42,70,105 all exceed 16, so each floor is 0; sum3=0. - Quadruple 210: ⌊16/210⌋=0. Then f(16)=16 - 18 + 5 - 0 + 0 = 3. So 3 valid u for M=16. 20) Compute f(3): - ⌊3/2⌋=1, ⌊3/3⌋=1, ⌊3/5⌋=0, ⌊3/7⌋=0; sum1=2. - Pairs: floors all 0 since lcms≥6; sum2=0. - Triples and quadruple also 0. So f(3)=3 - 2 + 0 - 0 + 0 = 1. So 1 valid u for M=3. 21) Compute f(21): - ⌊21/2⌋=10, ⌊21/3⌋=7, ⌊21/5⌋=4, ⌊21/7⌋=3; sum1=10+7+4+3=24. - Pairs: 6,10,14,15,21,35. Floors: ⌊21/6⌋=3, ⌊21/10⌋=2, ⌊21/14⌋=1, ⌊21/15⌋=1, ⌊21/21⌋=1, ⌊21/35⌋=0; sum2=3+2+1+1+1+0=8. - Triples: 30,42,70,105 all exceed 21 except 30; but 30>21 too. So all 0; sum3=0. - Quadruple: ⌊21/210⌋=0. Then f(21)=21 - 24 + 8 - 0 + 0 = 5. So 5 valid u for M=21. 22) Compute f(4): - ⌊4/2⌋=2, ⌊4/3⌋=1, ⌊4/5⌋=0, ⌊4/7⌋=0; sum1=3. - Pairs: lcms≥6, so all floors 0; sum2=0. - Triples and quadruple give 0. So f(4)=4 - 3 + 0 - 0 + 0 = 1. So 1 valid u for M=4. 23) Therefore, for each t we have: - t=35 (M=84): 20 values of u. - t=175 (M=16): 3 values of u. - t=875 (M=3): 1 value of u. - t=140 (M=21): 5 values of u. - t=700 (M=4): 1 value of u. Total number of k is the sum: 20 + 3 + 1 + 5 + 1 = 30. Each corresponds to a distinct k = t·u ≤ 2940 satisfying all gcd parity conditions. 24) Hence, the number of possible values of k with k ≤ N is 30.",
  "answer": "30"
}
